<paragraph blockId="11.[189,1399,510,854]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell" box="[189,405,510,536]" firstAuthor="Cockerell" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="139 - 149" refId="ref19678" refString="Cockerell T. D. A. 1912 c. XIV. - Description and records of bees. - XLI. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 9 (49): 139 - 149. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222931208693114" type="journal article" year="1912" yearSuffix="c">Cockerell (1912c)</bibRefCitation>
recognized the existence of two species similar to each other, which would have been identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1960" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[419,654,545,572]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haemorrhoidalis">
<emphasis box="[419,654,545,572]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. haemorrhoidalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. According to him, the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1960" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[1036,1271,545,572]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haemorrhoidalis">
<emphasis box="[1036,1271,545,572]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. haemorrhoidalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would be applied to Jamaican specimens where males have the first four terga and the anterior half of the fifth metallic blue, while females have the first four terga metallic blue and the rest reddish. Cockerell mentioned that the females from 
<collectingRegion box="[582,771,651,677]" country="Dominican Republic" name="Santo Domingo" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Santo Domingo</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[784,1028,651,677]" name="Dominican Republic" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Dominican Republic</collectingCountry>
identified by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lepeletier" box="[1193,1399,651,677]" firstAuthor="Lepeletier" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref21082" refString="Lepeletier A. L. M. 1841. Histoire naturelle des Insectes. Hymenopteres. Vol. II. Librairie encyclopedique de Roret, Paris." type="book" year="1841">Lepeletier (1841)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1960" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[225,458,686,713]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haemorrhoidalis">
<emphasis box="[225,458,686,713]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. haemorrhoidalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would correspond to a different species, since they have only the first three terga blue, proposing for them the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1912" box="[694,851,721,748]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lepeletieri">
<emphasis box="[694,851,721,748]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. lepeletieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell" box="[869,1086,721,748]" firstAuthor="Cockerell" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="139 - 149" refId="ref19678" refString="Cockerell T. D. A. 1912 c. XIV. - Description and records of bees. - XLI. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 9 (49): 139 - 149. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222931208693114" type="journal article" year="1912" yearSuffix="c">Cockerell (1912c)</bibRefCitation>
was correct in indicating the existence of two similar species. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1912" box="[761,917,757,783]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lepeletieri">
<emphasis box="[761,917,757,783]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. lepeletieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described based on specimens that correspond to the true 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1960" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[461,692,792,818]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haemorrhoidalis">
<emphasis box="[461,692,792,818]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. haemorrhoidalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The Jamaican species was described several decades later under the name 
<taxonomicName authority="Moure, 1960" authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1960" box="[377,677,827,854]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dirrhoda">
<emphasis box="[377,515,827,853]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. dirrhoda</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Moure" box="[522,677,827,854]" firstAuthor="Moure" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="97 - 160" refId="ref21372" refString="Moure J. S. 1960. Notes on the types of the Neotropical bees described by Fabricius (Hymenoptera: Apoidea). Studia Entomologica 3 (1 - 4): 97 - 160." type="journal article" year="1960">Moure, 1960</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[189,1399,893,990]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
One of the females studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lepeletier" box="[570,779,893,919]" firstAuthor="Lepeletier" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref21082" refString="Lepeletier A. L. M. 1841. Histoire naturelle des Insectes. Hymenopteres. Vol. II. Librairie encyclopedique de Roret, Paris." type="book" year="1841">Lepeletier (1841)</bibRefCitation>
was found at 
<collectionCode box="[958,1069,893,919]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">OUMNH</collectionCode>
and is here designated the 
<typeStatus box="[189,297,928,954]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1912" box="[337,550,928,954]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lepeletieri">
<emphasis box="[337,550,928,954]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Centris lepeletieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The specimen has the following data label: *Du [handwritten]\ 
<taxonomicName authority="Fabr Sto Domingo" authorityName="Fabr Sto Domingo" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haemorrhoidalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Centris haemorrhoidalis</emphasis>
Fabr Sto Domingo
</taxonomicName>
<specimenCount box="[617,640,964,990]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
.
</paragraph>
